1572","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1577":"1577","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","September 1583":"září 1583","1597":"1597","1585":"1585","1673":"1673","about 1557":"okolo 1557","1605":"1605","about 1571":"okolo 1571","1614":"1614","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Baldock, Hertfordshire, England":"Baldock, Hertfordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1557–before 27 June 1597":"omkring 1557–før 27. juni 1597","1550–1614":"1550–1614","1572–1605":"1572–1605","1575–1613":"1575–1613","1577–Female":"1577–Afdød","1583–1673":"1583–1673","1557–1597":"1557–1597","before 27 June 1597":"før 27. juni 1597","1572":"1572","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1577":"1577","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","September 1583":"september 1583","1597":"1597","1585":"1585","1673":"1673","about 1557":"omkring 1557","1605":"1605","about 1571":"omkring 1571","1614":"1614","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Baldock, Hertfordshire, England":"Baldock, Hertfordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1557–before 27 June 1597":"circa 1557–vóór 27 juni 1597","1550–1614":"1550–1614","1572–1605":"1572–1605","1575–1613":"1575–1613","1577–Female":"1577–Overleden","1583–1673":"1583–1673","1557–1597":"1557–1597","before 27 June 1597":"vóór 27 juni 1597","1572":"1572","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1577":"1577","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","September 1583":"september 1583","1597":"1597","1585":"1585","1673":"1673","about 1557":"circa 1557","1605":"1605","about 1571":"circa 1571","1614":"1614","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Baldock, Hertfordshire, England":"Baldock, Hertfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1557–before 27 June 1597":"about 1557–before 27 June 1597","1550–1614":"1550–1614","1572–1605":"1572–1605","1575–1613":"1575–1613","1577–Female":"1577–Deceased","1583–1673":"1583–1673","1557–1597":"1557–1597","before 27 June 1597":"before 27 June 1597","1572":"1572","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1577":"1577","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","September 1583":"September 1583","1597":"1597","1585":"1585","1673":"1673","about 1557":"about 1557","1605":"1605","about 1571":"about 1571","1614":"1614","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Baldock, Hertfordshire, England":"Baldock, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly North and Midlands) and Scottish: occupational name for a fuller, from Middle English <i>walker</i>, Old English <i>wealcere</i> (an agent derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’), ‘one who trampled cloth in a bath of lye or kneaded it, in order to strengthen it’. This was the regular term for the occupation during the Middle Ages in western and northern England. Compare   Fuller   and   Tucker  . As a Scottish surname it has also been used as a translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Fhucadair</b> ‘son of the fuller’. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","History: The name was brought to North America from northern England and Scotland independently by many different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Samuel Walker came to Lynn, MA, <i>c.</i> 1630; Philip Walker was in Rehoboth, MA, in or before 1643. The surname was also established in VA before 1650; a Thomas Walker, born in 1715 in King and Queen County, VA, was a physician, soldier, and explorer."],"variants":[{"name":"Walcher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunther, Hans, Horst, Klaus.","German: variant of   Walker   or   Walch  ."]},{"name":"Waker","meanings":["English (Yorkshire):","either a nickname for a watchful person or an occupational name for a watchman, from Middle English <i>waker</i> ‘watchful, vigilant’ (Old English <i>wacor</i>) and the derived noun.","mostly an early Modern English and Scots variant of   Walker  ."]},{"name":"Fuller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."]},{"name":"Walke","meanings":["German: metonymic occupational name for a fuller, from Middle High German <i>walke</i> ‘fulling mill’. Compare   Walker  .","English (Devon): variant of   Walk  ."]},{"name":"Walck","meanings":["German: variant of   Walker   or   Walch  ."]}]},{"name":"Augustine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Latin name <i>Augustinus</i> (a derivative of   Augustus  ). Its most famous bearer is  St Augustine  of Hippo (  354–430 ), perhaps the greatest of the Fathers of the Christian Church. He formulated the principles followed by the numerous medieval communities named after him as Austin canons, friars, and nuns. Also important in England was  St Augustine  of Canterbury, who brought Christianity to Kent in the 6th century.  See also  Austin ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":1,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":12,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":14,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":28,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":30,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Augustine Walker was born about 1557, in Hertfordshire, England. She married Augustine Walker about 1571, in England. They were the parents of at least 4 daughters. She died before 27 June 1597, in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1557–before 27 June 1597":"umbes 15